## Problem description ##

In angular one may use an injection token or an abstract class to register a service to the DI container (see [docs][1]).

However, neither technique seems to inform the developer **at compile time** about accidental mismatches between what shall be provided and what actually is provided. You can simply say, I provide an instance of `IBar`, while you actually supply a class `Foo` that does not satisfy the constraints of `IBar`.

In other languages such as C# or Java registering a service with an interface that does not match will instantly raise an error but it seems that with Typescript/Angular this is not the case which leaves room for accidental mismatches

## Question ##

How to achieve that an error is raised at compile time when registering a service with a typed token or abstract class inside `providers` when the provider does not match the type?

## Example ##

For example, both scenarios below will compile without errors but at runtime raise an error:

[![enter image description here][2]][2]

**Scenario 1 – Mismatch when using a typed token during configuration:**

```
import { BrowserModule } from &#39;@angular/platform-browser&#39;;
import { Component } from &#39;@angular/core&#39;;
import { NgModule, Inject, InjectionToken } from &#39;@angular/core&#39;;

interface IBar {
  getBar: () =&gt; string;
}

export class Foo {
  getFoo: () =&gt; string;
}

@Component({
  selector: &#39;app-main&#39;,
  template: &#39;&lt;h1&gt;Hello world&lt;/h1&gt;&#39;
})
export class MyComponent {
  constructor(@Inject(MyToken) bar: IBar) {
    // this will fail since Foo is injected by DI even though the
    // signature says IBar is received
    bar.getBar();
  }
}

export const MyToken = new InjectionToken&lt;IBar&gt;(&#39;foo&#39;);

@NgModule({
  declarations: [
    MyComponent
  ],
  imports: [
    BrowserModule,
  ],
  providers: [
    // note: we register Foo even though the token is typed with IBar
    // and the service also expects to receive IBar
    { provide: MyToken, useClass: Foo },
  ],
  bootstrap: [
    MyComponent
  ]
})
export class AppModule { }
```

**Scenario 2 – Mismatch when using an abstract class during configuration:**

```
import { BrowserModule } from &#39;@angular/platform-browser&#39;;
import { Component } from &#39;@angular/core&#39;;
import { NgModule } from &#39;@angular/core&#39;;

abstract class Bar {
  getBar: () =&gt; string;
}

class Foo {
  getFoo: () =&gt; string;
}

@Component({
  selector: &#39;app-main&#39;,
  template: &#39;&lt;h1&gt;Hello world&lt;/h1&gt;&#39;
})
class MyComponent {
  constructor(bar: Bar) {
    // this will fail since Foo is injected by DI even though the
    // signature says IBar is received
    bar.getBar();
  }
}

@NgModule({
  declarations: [
    MyComponent
  ],
  imports: [
    BrowserModule,
  ],
  providers: [
    // note: we register Foo even though the token is typed with IBar
    // and the service also expects to receive IBar
    { provide: Bar, useClass: Foo },
  ],
  bootstrap: [
    MyComponent
  ]
})
export class AppModule { }
```

